        <p>The Euclidean plane or rectangular coordinate system is formed by 
          two perpendicular copies of the real line intersecting at the number 
          <m>0</m> of each number line.  Each number of these number 
          lines is called an <term>axis</term>.  Points in the
          plane, called <term>ordered pairs</term>, are specified by 
          (horizontal position, vertical position).  
          The horizontal axis is often labeled <m>x</m> and the vertical axis <m>y</m>. 
          The point <m>(0,0)</m> is called the origin. The plane is divided 
